 ('2712', 'HTC', 'HTC Wildfire S T-Mobile', 280, 3.2, 156, 104.0, 59.0, 12.0, null, 'Smart phone', 'Android (2.3)', '320 x  480', 180, 'TFT', 5.0, null, 0.5, null, 1230, 6.7, 312.0, '3.0, EDR', 'GPS, A-GPS', 'manufacturer/HTC/HTC Wildfire S T-Mobile.jpg', 'This is the American version of the HTC Wildfire S, a mid-range Android smartphone, coming to T-Mobile. Fittingly, this budget friendly handset will be sporting the usual set of features such as a 3.2” display and an 600 MHz Snapdragon processor.'),
 ('2713', 'HTC', 'HTC Wildfire S', null, 3.2, 156, 101.3, 59.4, 12.4, '2011-02-15 00:00:00', 'Smart phone', 'Android (2.3)', '320 x  480', 180, 'TFT', 5.0, null, 0.5, null, 1230, 7.1, 360.0, '3.0, EDR', 'GPS, A-GPS', 'manufacturer/HTC/HTC Wildfire S.jpg', 'HTC Wildfire S comes to succeed the HTC Wildfire with a better HVGA screen and Android 2.3.3. It has 3.2" touchscreen, 5MP camera, Wi-Fi, GPS, Bluetooth and digital compass.'),
 ('2714', 'HTC', 'HTC Wildfire', 350, 3.2, 156, 106.7, 60.4, 12.9, '2010-05-17 00:00:00', 'Smart phone', 'Android (2.2, 2.1)', '240 x  320', 125, 'TFT', 5.0, null, 0.4, null, 1300, 8.16, 480.0, '2.1, EDR', 'GPS, A-GPS', 'manufacturer/HTC/HTC Wildfire.jpg', 'HTC Wildfire comes as a more compact and budget-friendly version of the HTC Desire. On the hardware side of things, the HTC Wildfire is not as spectacular as the Desire, but then again, it isn''t meant to be. It sports a 3.2-inch QVGA capacitive display, 5-megapixel camera with autofocus and LED flash, 3.5mm jack and microSD memory expansion. The processor inside is a 528MHz Qualcomm one.'),
 ('2715', 'HTC', 'HTC Windows Phone 8S', null, 4.0, 156, 120.5, 63.0, 10.28, '2012-09-19 00:00:00', 'Smart phone', 'Windows Phone, 8', '480 x  800', 233, 'S-LCD', 5.0, null, 0.5, 4.0, 1700, null, null, '3.1, EDR', 'GPS, A-GPS, Glonass', 'manufacturer/HTC/HTC Windows Phone 8S.jpg', 'The HTC Windows Phone 8S, the more affordable new Windows Phone 8 smartphone by HTC, has just been unveiled and it will enter direct competition with the Nokia Lumia 820.\nThe HTC 8S has a funky design with a brightly colored contrasted chin and a vividly colored earpiece. The device is pretty light at just 113 grams.\nThe hardware doesn’t shoot for the stars - instead it caters to budget minded consumers. We have a 4-inch WVGA (that’s 480 x 800 pixels) screen, a Snapdragon S4 chip with a 1.0GHz dual-core Krait processor, 512MB of RAM and 4GB of internal storage that you can expand via microSD cards. There is a removable panel at the bottom where HTC has placed the micro SIM and microSD card slots. The battery is not removable, though.\nHTC is including Beats Audio technology on this device to manage to differentiate itself in the Windows Phone arena.\nAt the back, we have a 5-megapixel camera with f/2.8 aperture, recording videos at 720p. One sore omission is a front facing camera, so there is no easy way to make video calls and make use of the built in Skype client.'),
 ('2716', 'HTC', 'HTC Windows Phone 8X', null, 4.3, 156, 132.3, 66.2, 10.1, '2012-09-19 00:00:00', 'Smart phone', 'Windows Phone, 8.1, 8', '720 x  1280', 342, 'S-LCD 2', 8.0, 2.0, 1.0, 16.0, 1800, 11.3, 290.0, '3.1, EDR', 'GPS, A-GPS, Glonass', 'manufacturer/HTC/HTC Windows Phone 8X.jpg', 'The 8X by HTC sports a 4.3" LCD 2 HD screen, which, if the One X display is any indication, should be a sight to behold, and has the respectable 342ppi pixel desnity. It ups the WP ante with a modern 28mm dual-core 1.5GHz Snapdragon S4 chipset, 1GB of RAM and 16GB of internal memory, thus equating its specs with the fierce WP8 competition in the face of the Samsung ATIV S, or the innovative Nokia Lumia 920, which, however, has a lot more going for it with the PureView camera.\nHow does the HTC 8X intend to differentiate from those? Why, Beats Audio, of course. The prominent branding is featured proudly on the back of the phone, promising deep bass sound and clearer audio. As for the sniping capabilities, we have an 8MP shooter on the rear with dedicated shutter key, equipped with HTC''s exclusive ImageSense technology, which is essentially a proprietary ISP, allowing for some additional photo trickery, like ultra fast capture times, and continuous shot mode that takes multiple frames per second. It sports ultra wide f/2.0 aperture, just like on the Lumia 920.'),
